he website below. These data are likely to be relevant to research on state strength and state failure, the dynamics of conflict, including security sector reform, demobilization and reintegration, as well as work on human rights and the interactions between different state and non-state actors.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>AB87B0B4-FC89-4820-BC1D-894B2F3A9946</gtr:id><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Government, Democracy and Justice,Security and Diplomacy</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors><gtr:url>http://www.sowi.uni-mannheim.de/militias-public</gtr:url></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/197F6C7A-E726-43E8-AB52-0995BB4F5862"><gtr:id>197F6C7A-E726-43E8-AB52-0995BB4F5862</gtr:id><gtr:title>The Impact of Pro-Government Militias on Human Rights Violations</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>International Interactions</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/0e53001552458977bcd54060ad6c6ae6"><gtr:id>0e53001552458977bcd54060ad6c6ae6</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Mitchell N</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2014-01-01</gtr:date></gtr:publication><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/B4AC7D9E-DCDE-48B6-9612-1479E902D8E8"><gtr:id>B4AC7D9E-DCDE-48B6-9612-1479E902D8E8</gtr:id><gtr:title>Pro-government militias, human rights abuses and the ambiguous role of foreign aid</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/bd033bfc42351eda04a56cc500fdb8a5"><gtr:id>bd033bfc42351eda04a56cc500fdb8a5</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Carey, SC</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2016-01-01</gtr:date></gtr:publication><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/4ABFB488-BB82-45D8-8516-9C0